Casuarina cunninghamiana

   [4337.jpg]
    Authority   Muell
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Hamamelidae:Casuarinales:Casuarinaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names beef wood
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 4337

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A medium sized to tall evergreen or deciduous tree
   20-30 m or up to 40 m tall, while the trunk is 50-150 cm in diameter.
   With short and soft branchlets. USES The wood makes a good fuel. The
   timber can be used for parquet flooring, packing cases, veneer, and
   barrel staves. Young trees are grazed by livestock and the tree
   provides good drought fodder. The tree can be used as an ornamental,
   for wind protection, shelterbelts, sand dune stabilisation, and
   riverbank and irrigation channel protection. A dye can be extracted
   from the leaves. It is mentioned as a possible agroforestry species.
   GROWING PERIOD Fast-growing and long-lived perennial. COMMON NAMES
   River sheoak, Creek oak, River oak, River-oak casuarina, Kasa,
   Beefwood, Australian pine, Pino Australiano, Pino de Australia, Pino,
   Pino de mar, Casuarina cavalinha, Mvinje, Jangli saru, Jan. FURTHER INF
   River sheoak is native of eastern and northern Australia. It can be
   found at elevations between sea level and 1000 m, and at latitudes
   between 12-38Â°S. As the tree is of riverine occurrence, rainfall alone
   is no indication of the total moisture requirement. It is mainly
   restricted to rivers and stream banks and adjacent valley flats, but it
   may extend for a short distance up rocky hillsides above watercourses.
   It is often planted along streams to protect river banks.
   Photosynthesis pathway C3. The tree fixes nitrogen.

